# Marketing sections must carry the logo print

Every full-bleed `<section>` on the marketing site (homepage and other
`(marketing)` pages) uses a faint repeating Networx logo watermark behind its
content via the `ButterflyPattern` component. When you add or substantially
restyle a marketing section, include the print so it stays consistent with the
rest of the page.

## How to apply

1. Make the section a positioning + clipping context: `className="relative overflow-hidden ..."`.
2. Add `ButterflyPattern` as the first child, absolutely filling the section.
3. Put the real content in a sibling wrapped with `relative z-10` so it sits above the print.

Pick the color by background:
- **Light / default background** → `colorClassName="text-primary"`, `opacity={0.1}`
- **Cyan (`bg-primary`) or dark background** → `colorClassName="text-primary-foreground"`, `opacity` ~`0.12`–`0.14`
- `tile` is typically `130`–`160`.

```tsx
import { ButterflyPattern } from '@/components/marketing/ButterflyPattern';

<section className="relative overflow-hidden py-16 border-b border-border">
  <ButterflyPattern className="absolute inset-0" colorClassName="text-primary" tile={140} opacity={0.1} />
  <div className="relative z-10 max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    {/* section content */}
  </div>
</section>
```

A section may already have a different absolute background (e.g.
`LiveRippleVisualizer`); add the print alongside it — both can coexist as long
as the content stays on `relative z-10`.

## Alternate teal ↔ light down the page

Stacked marketing sections alternate between **teal** and **light** so adjacent
sections never share the same background:

- **Teal section**: `bg-primary text-primary-foreground border-b border-primary-foreground/10`.
  Use `text-primary-foreground` (and `/80`, `/70` tints) for headings, body and
  links; for cards/media use `bg-primary-foreground/10`, `ring-primary-foreground/20`,
  and flip accent buttons to `bg-primary-foreground text-primary`. Print uses
  `colorClassName="text-primary-foreground"`.
- **Light section**: default background (`border-b border-border`, optionally
  `bg-muted`). Use `text-foreground` / `text-muted-foreground`. Print uses
  `colorClassName="text-primary"`.

When adding a new section, look at its neighbors and pick the opposite scheme so
the teal/light rhythm continues. Don't put two same-scheme sections back to back.
